<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Or: A Recovering Strong-2 Player’s Guide to Modern Enlightenment</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There I was, circa 1995, trying to learn bridge proudly playing Strong Two-Bids like my bridge from Basic Bridge by the great Ron Klinger written around 1991 teacher This book drills you like a military sergeant. “A Strong Two shows 22+ points OR 8.5+ playing tricks,”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Fast forward thirty and my first serious bridge lesson.  On a cruise from Southampton to the Adriatic coast with around 10 sea days and an amazing Irish bridge director.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The rules during the 10am beginner class the same as we remembered, the lessons in the 11;00 intermediate really well taught.  We didn’t even embarrass ourselves during afternoon play.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We are hooked and signed up to a local bridge club on our return to London.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Bidding boxes New, strident calls for Director!- New, thankfully not always at our table.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Something else new, Weak two’s nearly everyone is playing them but hey ho.  We have a plan ploughing on with not only “Basic bridge” but also “Better Acol Bridge, Duplicate Bridge, and Better Card Play.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We started out simple.  Too many conventions before the basics are second nature and all you do is make unforced errors, and we have always understood that club bridge is not about making Dubious slam bids or near psychic leads.  It’s about following the rules and not making as many mistakes as the room.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>So here we are following the plan, ACOL low 1NT, Stayman, Blackwood, Weak Jump overcalls, Strong 2’s.  Then a year later making our way through the lessons and practice, understanding the rules around 1x, 1NT rebid, Michael’s over Majors and unusual 2NT.  Let’s add transfers, great that worked with little or no pain.  How about Splinters and forcing 2NT, doesn’t come up all that often but WOW.  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>What’s next, oh you could dump strong 2’s by switching to weak because they come up more often and the pre-empt does more damage, it no, keep the benefits of strong 2’s and ADD weak 2 bids. Here we go!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Weak-2 Temptation (And My Stubborn Resistance)</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>By the mid 1990s, everyone and their bridge-playing grandmother had switched to Weak Twos. “Join us!” they’d cry. “Open 2♠ with 6-11 points and a good six-card suit! It’s preemptive! It’s descriptive! It’s fun!”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>But I missed all that so when we re started we held firm. “What about my game-forcing distributional monsters? You can’t just abandon them!”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Their solution? “Oh, just open 2♣ with everything strong. It’ll be fine.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>It is not fine.</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Opening 2♣ with:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>23 balanced</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>24 balanced</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Strong unbalanced hands</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Strong two-suiters</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Strong three-suiters</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>The kitchen sink</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>…is like using a sledgehammer to crack nuts, perform surgery, AND hang pictures. Theoretically possible, but wildly inefficient.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>All we had to do was wait, stick with the plan and hey presto</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Benjamin <strong>2</strong>♣ &amp; 2♦ System: Having Your Cake and Eating It Too</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Here’s the beautiful simplicity:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We move the old <strong>2</strong>♣ To <strong>2</strong>♦ with little change to how it’s played and reserve <strong>2</strong>♣ to indicate we are going to be bidding a strong 2 opening</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em>Genius!</em> Pure, unadulterated genius!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>2</strong>♣ = Game-forcing unbalanced hands (typically 20+ HCP 8 1/2 or 9 1/2 playing tricks, typically 5,6 or more in the suit or a balanced 23/24). The more cards in the suit the more wriggle room you have for points.  18-20 HCP and a 7 card suit<br /><strong>2</strong>♦ = Strong hands (typically 23 plus HCP we used to play this as <strong>2</strong>♣)<br /><strong>2</strong>♥<strong>/2</strong>♠ = Weak two-bids (6-11 HCP, good 6+ card suit)</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Mechanics: How This Magic Work</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" />
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading">Opening Sequences</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">After 2♣ Opening (Game-Forcing Unbalanced)</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Responder’s First move:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2♦ = Negative under 8 points and less than 1 1/2 quick tricks or occasionally no clear bid. Waiting bid</strong> (most common response, asks opener to describe their hand).  Everything else is positive.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2♥/2♠ = Natural, 5+ cards, decent suit</strong> (constructive but not promising much above 8 points)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2NT = Natural, balanced, 8-10 HCP</strong> (rare but possible)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>3♣/3♦/3♥/3♠ = Natural, 6+ cards, weak</strong> (pre-emptive style)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Opener After 2</strong>♣<strong> - 2</strong>♦<strong> (waiting):</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Count your quick playing tricks </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>AKQ in your long suit plus everything above three cards in that suit, add AK in O/S suits AQ = 1 1/2 Kx 1/2</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2♥/2♠ = 5+ card suit, forcing 8 1/2 quick tricks </strong></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2NT = Balanced 23-24 HCP</strong> (like old strong 2NT)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>3♣/3♦ = 6+ card suit, forcing 8 1/2 - 9 1/2 quick tricks usually 6 plus cards</strong></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>3♥/3♠ = 6 plus cards in the suit and exactly 9 tricks</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>4♥<strong>/</strong>4♠<strong> = 6 plus cards in the suit and 91/2 tricks</strong></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>4♣<strong>/</strong>4♦<strong> = 6+ card suit, forcing 9 1/2 - 10 quick tricks</strong> not suitable for 3NT less than 2 outside stoppers</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>5♣<strong>/</strong>5♦<strong> = 6+ card suit, forcing 10 1/2 quick tricks</strong>7 card suit not suitable for 3NT less than 2 outside stoppers</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>3NT = Solid minor suit</strong> two stopped suits 3NT. Opposite less than 1 1/2 tricks 3NT has more chance than 5 of the minor</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Opener After 2</strong>♣<strong> - any positive response </strong></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Bid slowly, you are committed to game and have slam possibility </li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">After 2♦ Opening (Strong Balanced 25 points or Unbalanced 23+ HCP or a hand with 10 playing tricks and 3 losers or better and a long major)</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Responder’s Options:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2</strong>♥<strong> = N</strong>egative 0-7 and less than 1 1/2 quick trick</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Anything else is positive with slam potential bid slow and natural</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>2NT = </strong>Balance 8 plus HCP - followed by <strong>3</strong>♣<strong> = Stayman</strong></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>3NT = To play</strong> (partner has shown 23+, you have 3+)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Key Advantages in Competition</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>When Opponents Interfere:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Double of interference = Usually penalty-oriented (you have the big hand)</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>New suits remain forcing after 2♣</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>After 2♦, systems remain on but with more flexibility to pass</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Slam Investigation:</strong><br />Since 2♣ shows game-forcing values, you have plenty of bidding room to explore slam. The 2♦ opening similarly provides a strong foundation for investigating 6NT or suit slams.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Common Auctions</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Example 1:</strong> 2♣ - 2♦; 2♥ - 2♠; 3♥ - 4♥<br /><em>Shows heart fit found, slam interest</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Example 2:</strong> 2♦ - 2NT; 3♦ - 3♥; 4♥ - Pass<br /><em>Stayman found 4-4 heart fit</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Example 3:</strong> 2♣ - 2♦; 3NT - Pass<br /><em>Solid minor suit, partner chooses final contract</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This system gives you the best of both worlds: the power of strong opening bids with the flexibility to show your hand type immediately.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

